        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7542.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Hensleigh Wedgwood, [3–9 March 1871]</ref>. A draft of this letter, together with additional notes made by CD after the letter was sent, is in DAR 88: 67. The notes reiterate CD’s discussion of remorse, using the example of the failure to save a drowning man. CD concludes: <quote type="quote"> In a 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Edit. I might say from several discussions &amp; correspondence with H.W. I have modified my views—given even more importance to praise &amp; blame, &amp; much less to endurance of social instincts. </quote> In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. 114, CD changed some of his discussion of remorse and referred to ‘critics’, but did not mention his exchange with Wedgwood on the topic.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD evidently enclosed the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7547.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from William Johnson, 5 March 1871</ref> (see CD’s annotations to the letter).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8251.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">H. Wedgwood 1866</ref> and H. Wedgwood 1859–[67]. CD’s annotated copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8251.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">H. Wedgwood 1866</ref> is in the Darwin Library–CUL (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi></ref> 1: 853).</note>
